You are implementing Phase C step 4/4: admin UI that surfaces a "Update available" Badge on skills with newer remote versions, plus an "Update" button that triggers `/admin/skills/:id/refresh-from-source`.

## Working directory

`/Users/vpulim/dev/ai/ax-next/.claude/worktrees/skills-versioning-phase-c`

## Branch state

Branch: `worktree-skills-versioning-phase-c` — stacked on Phase B (`worktree-skills-mcp-bundling-phase-b`). Three Phase C commits:
- `4904ce12` — `source_url` column + threading.
- `6896ea31` — manifest parses `sourceUrl`.
- `659e3071` — `skills:check-for-updates` hook + `/check-update` + `/refresh-from-source` admin routes.

`pnpm --filter @ax/skills test` → 98 passed.

## Confirmed component availability

`packages/channel-web` already has Badge, Button (and the rest of the shadcn primitives this UI needs). `AlertDialog` is NOT installed and is NOT needed — the plan listed it precautionarily but the actual UI in the plan's example only uses Badge + Button. No new shadcn installs.

## Files

- **Modify:** `packages/channel-web/src/lib/skills.ts` — add typed wire clients for the two new routes.
- **Modify:** `packages/channel-web/src/components/admin/SkillsTab.tsx` — fire check-update for each skill with sourceUrl on mount; show "Update available" badge + Update button when available.
- **Modify:** `packages/channel-web/src/components/admin/__tests__/SkillsTab.test.tsx` — test the new behavior.

## Step C.17 — Extend `packages/channel-web/src/lib/skills.ts`

Append:

```typescript
export interface CheckUpdateResult {
  available: boolean;
  currentVersion: number;
  latestVersion?: number;
  latestSkillMd?: string;     // present iff available === true
}

export async function checkSkillForUpdates(
  skillId: string,
): Promise<CheckUpdateResult> {
  const res = await fetch(
    `/admin/skills/${encodeURIComponent(skillId)}/check-update`,
    { method: 'POST', headers: csrfHeader, credentials: 'include' },
  );
  return (await handleResponse(res)) as CheckUpdateResult;
}

export interface RefreshResult {
  updated: boolean;
  currentVersion?: number;
  newVersion?: number;
}

export async function refreshSkillFromSource(
  skillId: string,
): Promise<RefreshResult> {
  const res = await fetch(
    `/admin/skills/${encodeURIComponent(skillId)}/refresh-from-source`,
    { method: 'POST', headers: csrfHeader, credentials: 'include' },
  );
  return (await handleResponse(res)) as RefreshResult;
}
```

`csrfHeader` is already defined in this file (`'x-requested-with': 'ax-admin'`); reuse it.

## Step C.17 — Extend `SkillsTab.tsx`

Add the following behavior:

1. State for per-skill update info:
   ```typescript
   const [updateInfo, setUpdateInfo] = useState<Record<string, CheckUpdateResult>>({});
   const [refreshingId, setRefreshingId] = useState<string | null>(null);
   ```
2. On mount (in addition to the existing `refresh()`), AND whenever `skills` changes, fire `checkSkillForUpdates(id)` for every skill that has a non-empty `sourceUrl`. Best-effort — swallow per-skill errors so a broken sourceUrl doesn't break the whole tab.
3. New handler `handleUpdate(skillId)`:
   ```typescript
   async function handleUpdate(skillId: string) {
     setRefreshingId(skillId);
     try {
       await refreshSkillFromSource(skillId);
       // re-fetch list + clear cached "available" state for this id so
       // the badge disappears immediately on success
       setUpdateInfo((prev) => {
         const next = { ...prev };
         delete next[skillId];
         return next;
       });
       await refresh();
     } catch (err) {
       setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err));
     } finally {
       setRefreshingId(null);
     }
   }
   ```
4. In each table row, after the existing `defaultAttached` Badge in the ID cell (or in a new cell — pick whichever fits the table layout cleanly), conditionally render:
   ```tsx
   {updateInfo[s.id]?.available && (
     <Badge variant="secondary" className="ml-2 text-xs">
       Update available: v{updateInfo[s.id].latestVersion}
     </Badge>
   )}
   ```
5. In the action-button cell (the last `<TableCell>` with the trash icon), add a new Update button BEFORE the edit/delete buttons, only when an update is available:
   ```tsx
   {updateInfo[s.id]?.available && (
     <Button
       variant="outline"
       size="sm"
       onClick={() => void handleUpdate(s.id)}
       disabled={refreshingId === s.id}
       aria-label={`Update ${s.id} to v${updateInfo[s.id].latestVersion}`}
     >
       Update
     </Button>
   )}
   ```
   Use the existing styling conventions in the file (no `space-x-*`, use `gap-*`).
6. Imports: add `checkSkillForUpdates`, `refreshSkillFromSource`, `type CheckUpdateResult` to the existing `@/lib/skills` import.

## Step C.17 — Test `SkillsTab.test.tsx`

Read the existing test file first to learn the patterns. It almost certainly stubs `listSkills` etc. Add at least these tests (match the existing test style — `vi.mock` for `@/lib/skills` if that's how it already does it, etc.):

1. **No badge when sourceUrl unset.** Mock `listSkills` to return a skill with no `sourceUrl`. Render. The "Update available" badge should NOT appear and `checkSkillForUpdates` should NOT have been called.
2. **Badge appears when check returns available:true.** Mock `listSkills` with one skill that has `sourceUrl: 'https://example.com/skill.md'`. Mock `checkSkillForUpdates` to return `{ available: true, currentVersion: 1, latestVersion: 2 }`. Render + await. Expect the badge text matches `/Update available.*v2/`.
3. **Update button triggers refresh + clears badge.** Same setup as test 2. Click the "Update" button. Expect `refreshSkillFromSource` to be called with the skill id. After it resolves, the badge should no longer be visible (the test can mock `listSkills` to return a skill with the new version on the second call so the post-refresh state has no badge).
4. **Check failure is swallowed (no spinner, no error in the alert).** Mock `checkSkillForUpdates` to throw. Render. Expect the badge to be absent and the error Alert to be absent (the existing `setError` is shared with the listSkills path, so we don't want a per-skill check failure to crowd the error surface — best-effort means silent).

Look at the file path pattern used by the existing tests — likely `@testing-library/react` + `vitest` + `vi.mock('@/lib/skills', ...)`.

## Verify

```
pnpm --filter @ax/channel-web test 2>&1 | tail -20
pnpm build --filter @ax/channel-web 2>&1 | tail -5
pnpm build 2>&1 | tail -5
```

All green.

## Commit

```
git add packages/channel-web/src
git commit -m "feat(skills): admin UI badge + Update button for sourceUrl refresh (Phase C step 4/4)"
```

## Report back

- Status: DONE / DONE_WITH_CONCERNS / BLOCKED / NEEDS_CONTEXT
- Per-file summary
- Test count before/after for @ax/channel-web (currently shows 454 passing)
- New commit SHA
- Anything surprising — especially if the existing test patterns don't match what was assumed in the test scaffold above

If `SkillsTab.test.tsx`'s existing structure doesn't match the assumptions in step C.17's test scaffold (e.g., it uses MSW instead of `vi.mock` for the wire), STOP and report BLOCKED with what the actual pattern is so the controller can re-scope.

